 Abstract 
 Previous studies on (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al hits/effects of bug-killer use have tended to focus either on measuring damages through 
 changes in relative risks to different (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories or examining the trade-off between bug-killer use levels and 
 stopping costs. This study uses the physical risk test approach combined with contingent (putting a value on something) survey results on 
 people' desire to reduce bug-killer risk. The reduction in external costs connected with the changes in bug-killer use 
 in Ontario farming between 1983 and 1998 is US$_$ 188 per household. (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al benefits are mostly due to the 
 reduction in the level of high and moderate-risk bug-killers. Â© 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 JEL classification: Ql2; Q29 
 Keywords: Money-based value; Bug-killers; Risk test 
 
 1. Introduction 
 The intensive use of bug-killers in farming has 
 increased (a lot) farming-based working well. The 
 on-farm benefits of bug-killer use are off-set to some 
 degree by the off-farm costs (forced (on people)/caused an inconvenient situation) by these bug-killers on the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions. (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) contamination from bug-killers ranges from the disruption of 
 natural water, air and soil functions, to the change 
 of the community resulting in harmful affects on 
 nutrient cycles, or the poisonous quality of non-target organisms. Concerns over these (effects on the surrounding conditions or on the health of the Earth) 
 have led to policy efforts ranging from moral suasion 
