 to rules to money-based legal documents, all designed 
 to reduce bug-killer use. Sound policy design needs/demands 
 an test of the benefits from a reduction in the 
 amount of bug-killer applied. 
 Approaches to testing the money-based effects of 
 reducing bug-killer use, specifically through integrated 
 pest management, have been reviewed (not very long ago) by 
 Swinton and Williams (1998). (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al hits/effects of bug-killer use are commonly proxied through 
 (numbers that change/things that change) such as pounds of active ingredient (a.i.) 
 applied or dollars spent on bug-killers. Both measures 
 assume that (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) damage is directly related to the amount of bug-killer used, (without any concern about/having nothing to do with) 
 the clearly stated/particular chemical and creation. Given the costs 
 of watching and measuring the extent of damages, 
 it is impossible to correctly decide/figure out the actual 
 damages of bug-killer use. Instead, damages have been 
 measured through changes in the relative risks to a 
 series of (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) and human health categories. 
 
