 An example is the work by Kovach et al. (1992) who 
 developed (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al hit/effect quotient (EIQ) 
 to decide/figure out the risk of bug-killers to the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions. The EIQ assigns a number to an a.i. based on 
 11 (features/ qualities/ traits) of the ingredient in order to calculate (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al parts/pieces of the indices. 
 Higley and Wintersteen (1992) followed by Mullen 
 et al. (1997) used eight separate judging requirements to describe (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk from insecticides, herbicides 
 and fungus-killers in calculating their surrounding conditionsally 
 (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) EIQs. Hoag and Hornsby (1992), Teague 
 et al. (1995), and Crissman et al. (1998) included 
 site-clearly stated/particular judging requirements in guessing (effects on the surrounding conditions or on the health of the Earth) or risks from bug-killers. Hoag and Hornsby 
 (1992) developed a trade-off edge of something/unexplored area for bug-killer 
 costs and a ground water danger-related index. The judging requirements 
 included bug-killer specific and site-clearly stated/particular judging requirements 
 that could affect the chance of ground water contamination. Teague et al. (1995) compared the EIQ 
 with site-specific guesses of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al future 
 of bug-killers, in addition to the poisonous quality and leakability measures in the EIQ. Crissman et al. (1998) also 
 included site-clearly stated/particular information on soil types and 
 rainfall in their measure of bug-killer leaking risk. 
 While these studies think about/believe (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al hits/effects and farm stopping costs of reducing risks, little 
 has been done on the money-based test of these 
 hits/effects. 
 The purpose of this paper is to identify the value 
 of (things that are good for the planet) connected with changes in 
 the levels and types of bug-killers applied in Ontario 
 farming. The approach is just like that developed 
 by Mullen et al. (1997) who extended the physical 
 risk test by incorporating a contingent (putting a value on something) survey to decide/figure out people' desire to 
 pay (CWP) for reductions in bug-killer risk to different 
 parts/pieces of the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions. The paper begins by 
 describing the method for assigning levels of relative 
 risk to the pesticidal a.i.s for eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories. The approach for valuing the changes in risk 
 from bug-killer use are then described. The changes 
 in bug-killer risk to (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions) from 1983 to 
 1998 are then organized and listed for all of Ontario farming. 
 The money-based value of changes in risks for the eight 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories are then described by time 
 period and by risk level. Factors adding/giving to the 
 changes and later policy effects/results/suggestions are then 
 discussed. 
 
 2. Methods 
 2.1. Identifying changes in bug-killer risk to the 
 (surrounding conditions) 
 The (possibility of/possible happening of)  a bug-killer to cause external damage costs (risk) is measured using an approach developed by Mullen et al. (1997). Rather than assume 
 the amount applied is an correct substitute for risk, the 
 approach recognises that risks change/differ  with bug-killers 
 depending on their poisonous quality, ability to move around and toughness. 
 Mullen et al. (1997) develop a set of judging requirements for assigning levels of relative risk to pesticidal a.i.s for 
 eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) and human health categories; 
 ground water, surface water, sudden human health, 
 long-lasting human health, water-based species, birds, (milk-producing animals), and insects. Each a.i. was assigned a risk 
 level of high, (not an extreme person), or low for each (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) category. For example, atrazine is categorised as 
 a high (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk to ground water, a medium 
 risk to surface water, water-based species, sudden and 
 long-lasting health, and a low-risk to birds, (milk-producing animals) and 
 non-target organisms. A list of the risk levels created by/presented by 
 all the bug-killers used in Ontario for each of the eight 
 categories is available from the authors upon request. 
 The approach this way permits the measurement of the 
 change in total kilograms of bug-killer within each of 
 the 24 risk per (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) classes (the three levels 
 of risk for each of the eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories). 
 For example, the 585,208 kg of atrazine a.i. applied to 
 corn in 1993 were set apart and given out to the appropriate risk per 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) classes as defined above. The amount 
 of each bug-killer applied was (in almost the same way) gave out. The 
 total amounts for all bug-killers for each class were 
 then summed to decide/figure out the total high, medium and 
 low-risk per (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) category per survey year. 
 This total within a given (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth)/risk category 
 can be expressed as 
