 2.2. (putting a value on something) of changes in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk 
 
 importance; 
 
 WTPu = 
 While the change in risk from bug-killer use can be 
 tested by comparing the amount of bug-killer applied 
 within each risk level across years, this would not account for the greater benefits attached to a reduction 
 in high against/compared to/or low-risk bug-killer use. One method to 
 weight, the changes in use for different risk levels 
 is to assign money-based values to these changes. Since 
 reducing bug-killer risk is not a market valuable thing, 
 the value of the changes in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk connected with changes in bug-killer use must be guessed 
 through a non-market (putting a value on something) way of doing things. The guesses used in this study are based on the results of 
 a contingent (putting a value on something) survey given to a random sample of 3000 families in the United States 
 by Mullen et al. (1997). The list of questions began by 
 asking for the person who responded's monthly grocery bill followed by questions on the person's desire to 
 pay to avoid a given level of risk to (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions) 
 and human health through an increase in that grocery 
 bill. The people who responded were asked to show their desire to pay for each of the three risk levels (WTPj, 
 j = 1-3) rather than their WTP for a reduction in risk 
 for each of the eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories with 
 each risk level (WTPij ). So, the received/got WTP j for 
 WTPij is assumed to be the sum of the WTP to reduce 
 risk within each (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) category. However, the 
 three WTP j values were not split equally among the 
 eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories since is it is assumed 
 that reducing bug-killer use that is high-risk to humans, 
 for example, is valued more than a similar reduction in bug-killer use that is high-risk to insects. 
 The showed/told about WTP j values were used to guess  the 
 eight WTPij values for that risk level through a ranking that the people assigned to (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al 
 categories. People who responded were asked to identify how 
 
