 a.i. connected with each risk level j and for each 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) category I (l- (Useijt!USei}t-d) multiplied by the similar value for the person's 
 WTPij. Decreases (increases) in usage for any (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth)/risk category will reduce (increase) the 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk costs. However, savings can be 
 created even if there is no change in total bug-killer 
 use between periods, if there is a relative change in the 
 level of risks created by/presented by the same amount of a.i. For example, benefits are created if there is a move/change toward 
 low-risk bug-killers and away from high-risk ones, 
 since the WTP values are higher for high-risk than for 
 low-risk uses. (in almost the same way), a reduction in the dollar value of (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk happens if the relative changes happen for an (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) category for 
 which the WTP is high. The approach does not account 
 for the total level of bug-killer use so that a (fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else) reduction of bug-killers when a large amount is 
 applied is valued the same as when the total amount of 
 use is small. The approach assumes a linear relationship between the percentage risk reduction and actual 
 risk eliminated within each category since, WTP values are based on how much people would be willing to pay to avoid a risk while the actual changes in 
 bug-killer use result in only a fraction of the risk being 
 eliminated. 
 
 3. Data and results 
 3.1. Data 
 
 The Ontario Ministry of Farming Food and (away from cities) Affairs has surveyed growers every five years since 
 1973 to collect a record of the use of herbicides, 
 insecticides, and fungus-killers in Ontario crop production. The survey collects the area of each crop grown 
 ((anyway/in any event) of whether it was sprayed or not), the 
 amount of product applied to an area, the number of 
 times a crop is sprayed, and its PCP number that points to/shows the strength of the product and the multiple 
 a.i.s in the case of mixtures. The individual grower 
 data is then grouped up to the county and (related to a local area) level based on production shares. This publicly 
 available, grouped data is used in this study to 
 compare changes in use patterns and to document 
 progress made in bug-killer and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk 
 reduction. 
 
 3.2. Results 
 3.2.1. Changes in bug-killer risk to (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions) 
 The total amount of bug-killers applied in Ontario 
 has (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) about 40% from 8.8 million kg 
 of a.i. in 1983 to 5.2 million kg of a.i. in 1998 (Table 2). 
 The change in the total amount of bug-killer use was 
 connected mostly with a decrease in application rates. 
 Some of the reduced rate (9%) is indirectly attributable 
 to a government program called Food Systems 2002. 
 This program gave money (to) research and educational activities into bug-killer management with the goal of 
 reducing bug-killer use in the area of control/area of land of Ontario by 
 50% over a 15-year-period ending in 2002. However, 
 the decrease in the total amount applied is due mostly 
 to two major changes in production practices related 
 to bug-killers during this period. The first change was 
 a 20% reduction in the total area of land farmed, and 
 the second was a move/change in cropping patterns from corn 
 to soybeans. Soybeans generally require less herbicide 
 than corn and the increased use of a com-soybean rotation reduced the need for insecticide compared with 
 continuous com. 
 The amount and share of the once-a-year total amount 
 applied classified by risk level are given for the eight 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories in Table 2. Most 
 the bug-killers applied are not carefully thought about/believed high-risk for 
 any of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al groupings. In 1983, high-risk 
 bug-killers represented more than one-quarter of the 
 total amount applied for only the ground water and 
 long-lasting human categories. The total amount and share 
 of bug-killers that are high-risk for these categories 
 declined over time, especially in terms of long-lasting 
 human effects. However, there has been an increase 
 in the relative share of total bug-killers applied that 
 represent a high-risk to water-based species, surface water and acute human categories. The share of the total applied that is high-risk for these groupings is about 20%. This increase in the relative share 
 of high-risk bug-killers for these three (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories came as a result of a decrease in the 
 amount of moderate-risk bug-killers applied. For all 
 categories, with the exception of insects, the total 
 amount of bug-killers that are moderate-risk has fallen 
 significantly in both total amounts and as a share 
 of the total. Yet around half of all bug-killers applied 
 are carefully thought about/believed moderate-risk to surface water, water-based 
 species, and long-lasting human categories. For the last 
 
