 The percentage changes in the amount of bug-killer 
 applied by risk category between 1983 and 1998 are 
 listed in Table 3. The percentage changes are important for the (putting a value on something) exercise to follow as the WTP 
 values refer to the complete elimination of risk. The 
 (figuring out how much money something is worth) multiply the WTP values (Table l) by these 
 percentage changes as noted in Eq. (4). There has been 
 big reduction in the total amount of bug-killer that is carefully thought about/believed high and moderate-risk for most 
 of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al categories. The amount of bug-killer that is high-risk for surface water and acute human categories has increased between 1983 and 1998 
 by 67 and 31%, (match up each pair of items in order). While, the percentage 
 increases are significant, the total amount still represents less than one-third of the total amount of bug-killer applied by risk category. The use of moderate-risk 
 
 bug-killers fell for all (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories except 
 insects. As discussed above, most of the 
 bug-killers applied are carefully thought about/believed low-risk for this category. The amount that is moderate-risk for insects 
 increased from 0.19 million kg of a.i. in 1983 to 0.69 
 million kg of a.i. in 1998 but this amount represents 
 13% of the total applied. In summary, most of the 40% 
 decrease in the total amount applied between 1983 and 
 1998 is due to a decrease in high and moderate-risk 
 bug-killers for most of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al categories. 
 
 3.2.2. (putting a value on something) of changes in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk 
 The values of the changes in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risks 
 created by/presented by bug-killers in Ontario tested using Eq. (4) 
 are listed in Table 4. The values point to/show the amount an 
 average household would be willing to pay every year 
 to experience the percentage change in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) 
 risk watched/followed for each time period. The reduction in 
 external costs connected with the changes in bug-killer 
 use between 1983 and 1998 is US$_$ 188 per household 
 every year. Since the total number of families in Ontario in 1993 was 3,781,440, the value of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al risk reduction for the whole area of control/area of land over the 
 last 15 years was 711 million (Canadian)$_$. 
 The largest reduction happened in the last 5-yearperiod with mostly no benefits connected with 
 changes between 1988 and 1993. The value of the 
 change in bug-killer risk was greatest between 1993 
 and 1998 since the changes in risk were positive for 
 all eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories. The largest benefits built up (match up each pair of items in order) to mammalian species, bird-related 
 species, long-lasting human, ground water and water-based 
 species. These results are due to the large percentage 
 reduction in the total amount of bug-killer applied 
 
