 4. Ends/end results 
 Designing sound policies to reduce bug-killer use needs/demands an test of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al benefits that 
 can be compared with the stopping costs for bug-killer users and the (related to managing and running a company or organization) costs of enforcing the 
 policy. Previous studies of (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al hits/effects 
 of bug-killer use have tended to focus either on measming damages through changes in relative risks to 
 different (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories on or examining the 
 trade-off between bug-killer use levels and stopping 
 costs. This study uses the physical risk test 
 approach combined with contingent (putting a value on something) survey 
 results on consumer's desire to reduce bug-killer 
 risk. The method developed by Mullen et al. ( 1997) 
 is used to identify the value of (things that are good for the planet) 
 from changes in the level and types of bug-killers applied in Ontario farming. The total amount of bug-killers applied in Ontario has (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) about 
 40% from 8.8 million kg of a.i. in 1983 to 5.2 million 
 kg of a.i. in 1998. Only for the surface water category 
 were high-risk bug-killers more than one-quarter of the 
 total amount applied in 1998. The total amount and 
 share of bug-killers that are high-risk for most (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) categories (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) over time, especially in 
 terms of long-lasting human and mammalian species effects. There was a almost the same  decrease in the amount of 
 bug-killers used that are carefully thought about/believed moderate-risk with 
 
 226 
 
