 the exception of the insect (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) category. 
 The reduction in total amount applied is due mostly to 
 the reduction in high and moderate-risk categories as 
 the percentage change in low-risk bug-killer use averaged to zero across the eight (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) groups. 
 The reduction in external costs connected with 
 the changes in bug-killer use between 1983 and 1998 
 is US$_$ 188 per household every year, which represents a value of US$_$ 711 million for the area of control/area of land 
 as a whole. Once again, (the health of the Earth/the surrounding conditions)al benefits can be attributed to the reduction in the level 
 of high and moderate-risk bug-killer use. The percentage decreases noted for the total amount applied 
 are weighted by the desire to pay to eliminate risks, with higher values connected with higher 
 risks. In most cases, the categories experienced a 
 reduction in external costs due to reductions in the 
 use of bug-killers that are carefully thought about/believed high-risk. Over 
 70% of the total value connected with the reduction in (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) risk is due to the reduction of 
 high-risk bug-killer use. The overall external costs of 
 low-risk bug-killers have increased since 1983 due 
 to the increase in use of these bug-killers in the categories ground water, surface water and sudden and 
 long-lasting human health. However, this small increase 
 in cost connected with increased low-risk bug-killer 
 use is still significantly smaller than the value of the 
 
 (things that are good for the planet) that results from the reduced 
 use of bug-killers thought about/believed high and moderate-risk. 
